nterviews topically to bring out different aspects of the Chicano vets' experiences. In addition to discussing their involvement in and views on the Vietnam War, the veterans also reflect on their place in American society, American foreign policy, and the value of war. Veterans from several states and different socioeconomic classes give the book a broad-based perspective, which Ybarra frames with sociological material on the war and its impact on Chicanos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexican American soldierszVietnam. 0aVeteranszUnited States. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975vPersonal narratives, American. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xParticipation, Mexican Americans. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xVeteranszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aHeredia, Juan Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlmos, Edward James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlmos, Edward James.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70225740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798496/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK